==Colours and badge==
The club's original colours were blue and white and not the current blue and yellow. The club's historic nickname is ''Gialloblu'' (from the club colours of yellow and blue), although throughout Italian football, the Verona's team recognised in the past by most fans as ''Gialloblu'' are Hellas Verona, Chievo's main rivals. Local supporters often call the club simply ''Ceo'', which is Venetian for Chievo. The club is now sometimes referred to as the ''I Mussi Volanti'' ("The Flying Donkeys" in the Verona dialect of [[Venetian language|Venetian]]). "The Flying Donkeys" nickname was originally used by fans from crosstown rivals [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas]] to mock Chievo. The [[Derby della Scala|two clubs first met]] in Serie B in the mid-1990s, with Hellas chanting ''Quando i mussi volara, il Ceo in Serie A'' — "Donkeys will fly before Chievo are in Serie A." However, once Chievo earned [[2001–02 Serie A|promotion to Serie A]] at the end of the [[2000–01 Serie B|2000–01 Serie B season]], Chievo fans started to call themselves "The Flying Donkeys".<ref name="Late Tackle">{{cite web|url=https://www.latetacklemagazine.com/features/427/chievo-verona/ |title=Chievo: Fairytale of the Flying Donkeys |first=Edd |last=Paul |publisher=Late Tackle |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>

The current club crest represents [[Cangrande I della Scala]], a medieval lord of Verona.

==Stadium==
Stadio Marcantonio Bentegodi is a stadium in Verona, Italy. It is also the home of Chievo Verona city rival Hellas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chievoverona.tv/it/content/come-raggiungere-lo-stadio |title=Chievo Verona official website |accessdate=4 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110512144258/http://www.chievoverona.tv/it/content/come-raggiungere-lo-stadio |archivedate=12 May 2011 }}</ref>

Inaugurated as a state-of-the-art facility and as one of Italy's finest venues in 1963, the stadium appeared excessive for a team (Hellas) that had spent the best part of the previous 35 years in Serie B. For the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] renovations included an extra tier and a roof to cover all sections, improved visibility, public transport connections, an urban motorway connecting the city centre with the stadium and the Verona Nord motorway exit and services.

